n the early PRC sought to escape their villages for a more prosperous","box":[[135,808],[880,808],[880,832],[135,832]]},{"text":"lifeinsidetheurbanwelfaresystem.AttemptstomeasureMaoeraurbanization","box":[[135,836],[879,837],[879,860],[135,859]]},{"text":"statistically are complicated by the fact that state definitions of “urban areas\"” were","box":[[135,865],[880,864],[880,888],[135,889]]},{"text":"not consistent across the decades.Different datasets alsodisagree onhow totreat","box":[[135,896],[880,896],[880,919],[135,919]]},{"text":"the suburban agricultural population, which was sometimes considered part of the","box":[[136,925],[878,925],[878,948],[136,948]]},{"text":"“population of cities and towns”and sometimes excluded.7°Another quirk in the","box":[[138,954],[880,953],[880,976],[138,977]]},{"text":"data is the Mao-era practice of including workers in factories located outside the","box":[[135,981],[880,982],[880,1006],[135,1005]]},{"text":"cities in the non-agricultural (i.e. urban) population statistics.","box":[[135,1013],[697,1013],[697,1036],[135,1036]]},{"text":"With these caveats in mind, let us examine the figures. According to official","box":[[158,1041],[880,1041],[880,1064],[158,1064]]},{"text":"statistics, the years between 1949 and 1961 saw an increase of the urban popula.","box":[[136,1070],[876,1070],[876,1093],[136,1093]]},{"text":"tionfrom around1otoI9percent of the national total.Thepost-famine","box":[[136,1098],[878,1098],[878,1121],[136,1121]]},{"text":"\"sending down” of 26 million workers reduced this to 14 percent in 1964,","box":[[137,1126],[878,1128],[878,1152],[137,1150]]},{"text":"before a slight uptick in the following years. During the Cultural Revolution","box":[[134,1154],[881,1155],[881,1181],[134,1180]]},{"text":"(1966-1976), the urbanization rate held steady at around 17 percent.","box":[[137,1186],[878,1186],[878,1209],[137,1209]]},{"text":"7oThomasScharping,“Urbanization in China since 1949,”TheChinaQuarterly,No.1o9(1987